WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.880
I will switch here from GVHD to conditioning regimen.

00:00:05.120 --> 00:00:07.180
So this is...

00:00:07.180 --> 00:00:17.600
Thank you.

00:00:18.360 --> 00:00:24.960
All right, so I will talk about the use of the next-generation radiominal therapy

00:00:24.960 --> 00:00:27.820
using the alpha-ammeter as part of the conditioning regimen

00:00:27.820 --> 00:00:30.040
for a patient with high-risk leukemia.

00:00:30.440 --> 00:00:32.020
I have no disclosure for this one.

00:00:32.420 --> 00:00:36.000
So we all know that the main problem in conditioning regimen

00:00:36.000 --> 00:00:39.380
is still the trade-off between the toxicity and relapse.

00:00:39.840 --> 00:00:43.260
Reduced-intensity conditioning could help to reduce significantly

00:00:43.260 --> 00:00:47.540
the treatment-related mortality from 25% to about 10%,

00:00:47.540 --> 00:00:52.960
but it comes at the price of significantly higher risk

00:00:52.960 --> 00:00:54.940
of the relapse.

00:00:54.960 --> 00:00:59.700
So we know for decades that radiation works.

00:01:00.120 --> 00:01:03.640
This is a landmark randomized trial from Fred Hutch

00:01:03.640 --> 00:01:07.620
almost three decades ago showing us very clearly here

00:01:07.620 --> 00:01:13.000
the dose effect of radiation to relapse rates of patients with ALL.

00:01:13.560 --> 00:01:18.400
So higher-dose TBI could significantly decrease the relapse

00:01:18.400 --> 00:01:23.780
from 35% to 12%, but again, the benefit is offset

00:01:23.780 --> 00:01:24.520
by higher-dose TBI.

00:01:24.520 --> 00:01:24.520
So we know for decades that radiation works.

00:01:24.520 --> 00:01:24.700
So we know for decades that radiation works.

00:01:24.700 --> 00:01:24.940
So higher-dose TBI could significantly decrease the relapse from 35% to 12%,

00:01:24.940 --> 00:01:26.020
but again, the benefit is offset by higher-dose TBI.

00:01:26.020 --> 00:01:26.680
So higher-dose TBI could significantly decrease the relapse from 35% to 12%,

00:01:26.680 --> 00:01:26.720
but again, the benefit is offset by higher-dose TBI.

00:01:26.720 --> 00:01:30.300
There's one way to enhance the anti-tumor efficacy

00:01:30.300 --> 00:01:35.300
and reduce the toxicity of radiation is to target the radiation

00:01:35.300 --> 00:01:39.640
to the site of the malignancy and spare the normal tissues.

00:01:40.220 --> 00:01:44.920
So the RIT concept pioneered by the researchers at Fred Hutch.

00:01:45.260 --> 00:01:51.400
So in RIT, we use a monoclonal antibody as a kind of biological vehicle

00:01:51.400 --> 00:01:54.680
conjugated with radiation isotope to deliver radiation.

00:01:54.680 --> 00:01:56.060
So in RIT, we use a monoclonal antibody as a kind of biological vehicle conjugated with radiation

00:01:56.060 --> 00:01:58.460
to the site of the disease, like bone marrow spleen,

00:01:59.200 --> 00:02:03.720
and with very minimized toxicity to the surrounding tissue.

00:02:03.720 --> 00:02:11.860
So two key elements of RIT, the target antigen for patient with he malignancy AML,

00:02:11.860 --> 00:02:19.440
the CD45, have been used very commonly because of its broad expression on hematopoietic cells

00:02:19.440 --> 00:02:24.660
and very limited expression on the non-hematopoietic cells, and the other component is,

00:02:24.660 --> 00:02:26.140
the radiation isotope.

00:02:26.140 --> 00:02:39.060
So the first generation RIT, you know, we use the beta particles like iodide-131 and yttrium-90

00:02:39.060 --> 00:02:44.040
because of, you know, it varies based on the availability,

00:02:44.040 --> 00:02:51.540
the experience for their critical use, together with the radiolabeling technology.

00:02:51.540 --> 00:02:52.120
Okay.

00:02:52.120 --> 00:03:01.720
So the beta-emitter platform, like IOMAP, have been shown yesterday that the feasibility

00:03:01.720 --> 00:03:09.780
and the ability to scale across the center, however, for the beta particles, they have

00:03:09.780 --> 00:03:16.120
relatively long path length and also lower radiation deposition.

00:03:16.120 --> 00:03:21.860
So this allows the post-fire effects, but it also leads to the higher radiation exposure

00:03:21.860 --> 00:03:24.080
to the surrounding tissue.

00:03:24.080 --> 00:03:30.360
On the other hand, the beta particles have very different physical properties.

00:03:30.360 --> 00:03:35.620
They have significantly shorter path length and higher linear energy transfer.

00:03:35.620 --> 00:03:43.460
So that instead of having diffuse radiation, we now would have very highly precise and

00:03:43.460 --> 00:03:51.600
potent radiation to deliver to the site of the malignancy while minimizing the exposure

00:03:51.600 --> 00:03:53.940
of the surrounding tissues.

00:03:53.940 --> 00:03:58.100
So this is the pre-clinical murine models.

00:03:58.100 --> 00:04:07.440
We can see that acetine-211 label with the anti-CD45 show the dose effect bone marrow

00:04:07.440 --> 00:04:09.820
suppression very clearly here.

00:04:09.820 --> 00:04:15.120
So at a lower dose, the 10-microcurie, we can see, you know, transient bone marrow suppression

00:04:15.120 --> 00:04:21.340
with hypocellularity about 24, 48 hours, and then after that, at one week, the marrow recovery,

00:04:21.340 --> 00:04:22.580
it will recover.

00:04:22.580 --> 00:04:28.100
When the dose increased to 20 microcurie, we can observe deeper cytopenia later about

00:04:28.100 --> 00:04:30.840
two weeks and then recovery about three weeks.

00:04:30.840 --> 00:04:36.500
When the dose gets higher to 50 microcurie, so this transition to really irreversible

00:04:36.500 --> 00:04:40.000
myeloblation and really lethal cytopenia.

00:04:40.000 --> 00:04:47.440
So this is very important, and this is, you know, provides a very strong rationale for

00:04:47.440 --> 00:04:51.080
clinical translation, this to the transplant conditioning.

00:04:51.080 --> 00:04:58.120
So that's led to our first in-human trial at Fred Hutch when we combined the acetine

00:04:58.120 --> 00:05:05.120
label with CD45 monoclonal antibody with our backbone flu low-dose TBI conditioning regimen

00:05:05.120 --> 00:05:08.200
for patient-received matched donors.

00:05:08.200 --> 00:05:14.140
So this study design with the two-stage approach, a stage one dose fighting to identify the

00:05:14.140 --> 00:05:20.820
maximum tolerated dose and the expansion cohort in stage two, so we enrolled 45 patients so

00:05:20.820 --> 00:05:21.360
far.

00:05:21.360 --> 00:05:24.860
This is the first 20 patients with excellent follow-up time.

00:05:24.860 --> 00:05:31.540
This is the patient with, you know, very extensive history of the treatment before, including

00:05:31.540 --> 00:05:34.500
three patients with prior allo transplant.

00:05:34.500 --> 00:05:40.960
So this is the table to show you in more details of the patient characteristics with the pre-transplant

00:05:40.960 --> 00:05:41.920
bone marrow blast.

00:05:41.920 --> 00:05:46.120
Fifty percent of those patients had active disease at time of transplant with the blast

00:05:46.120 --> 00:05:49.260
